        <!-- Project Overview -->
        <div class="project-section">
            <h3>Project Overview</h3>
            <p>
                This project demonstrates a <strong>Continuous Integration / Continuous Deployment (CI/CD)</strong> workflow for WordPress on AWS:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Source:</strong> GitHub repository with WordPress and CloudFormation templates.</li>
                <li><strong>Pipeline:</strong> AWS CodePipeline automating deployment on every new commit.</li>
                <li><strong>Infrastructure:</strong> AWS CloudFormation provisioning EC2 instance, MySQL DB, Apache, PHP, and WordPress.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>The goal was to achieve <strong>automated, repeatable deployments</strong> without manual intervention.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Architecture -->
        <div class="project-section alt-bg">
            <h3>Architecture Explanation</h3>
            <p>The workflow integrates GitHub with AWS services:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>GitHub</strong> – Stores the WordPress application code and infrastructure templates.</li>
                <li><strong>AWS CodePipeline</strong> – Monitors GitHub for changes and orchestrates deployment.</li>
                <li><strong>S3 Bucket</strong> – Stores artifacts from each pipeline run.</li>
                <li><strong>AWS CloudFormation</strong> – Reads the <code>wordpress-app.yaml</code> template and provisions resources.</li>
                <li><strong>EC2 Instance</strong> – Hosts Apache, PHP, MySQL, and WordPress.</li>
                <li><strong>Security Group</strong> – Allows HTTP (80) and restricted SSH (22) access.</li>
                <li><strong>Outputs</strong> – Provides the WordPress site URL for immediate access.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Key Learnings -->
        <div class="project-section">
            <h3>Key Learnings</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Set up <strong>GitHub → AWS CodePipeline</strong> integration with webhooks.</li>
                <li>Created IAM roles for CodePipeline and CloudFormation with correct permissions.</li>
                <li>Automated deployment of WordPress using CloudFormation templates.</li>
                <li>Observed how CodePipeline fetches changes from GitHub and redeploys automatically.</li>
                <li>Understood the importance of <strong>Infrastructure as Code</strong> and CI/CD in cloud projects.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Best Practices -->
        <div class="project-section alt-bg">
            <h3>Notes & Best Practices</h3>
            <p>
                This project deployed WordPress on a single EC2 instance for learning purposes. In production:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Databases should run on <strong>Amazon RDS</strong> instead of local MySQL for scalability.</li>
                <li>Static media files can be served from <strong>S3 + CloudFront</strong> for performance.</li>
                <li><strong>Auto Scaling</strong> with Load Balancers improves high availability.</li>
                <li>Restrict SSH access to specific IP addresses only.</li>
                <li>Use separate pipelines for <strong>staging and production</strong> environments.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

